Whisk(e)y lovers, we have some precious information for you.

Whisky is made in Scotland, and is usually distilled twice. Boring you might think. But, did you know that Whiskey with an E, is usually made in Ireland or in the US ! 

Another fact that will blow you mind : every second, 200 liters of whisky are being drunk around the globe .

We'll have a glass .. cheers !
.
.
.

Let us introduce you to Seoul's motto “work hard, play harder”.

French restaurateur Luc Sananes will take you on a 𝘽𝘼𝙍 𝙃𝙊𝙋𝙋𝙄𝙉𝙂 journey to discover the best bars in the capital – and sample delicious whisky cocktails in the process.

Starting at Pussyfoot Saloon, before heading over to Gangnam‘s Le Chamber, an elegant lounge hidden behind a magical bookcase. A quick bite, a few beers and a short night’s sleep later, we followed Luc to trendy Euljiro to discover another hidden gem called Jean Frigo, set in a traditional Korean house accessible through a fridge inside a grocery store. 

We won't leak more details, watch the journey and enjoy !

Videographer : Brice VDH @bricevdh
Host : Luc Sananes @lucsananes

Full version on our Youtube channel - link in bio

"Featuring craft cocktails and small-batch spirits, this Mexican-inspired bar in Hong Kong has the largest selection of agave spirits in the city, handpicked  in Mexico by Jay Khan, one of Hong Kong’s most respected bartenders, himself. The mezcal and tequila bar’s impressive array of directly sourced, small batch spirits and its classic and innovative cocktails that highlight their distinctive aromas have turned it into a Hong Kong nightlife success story. 

Cocktail-wise, if you’ve never really ventured beyond the margarita, the Paloma de Oaxaca, combining mezcal joven, blanco tequila, grapefruit soda and zest, lime, and sal de gusano, is a great place to start. 

Jay and his knowledgeable staff are on hand to guide newcomers through the complexities of the agave world. Let yourself be guided ... and cheers !"

node.text:
We’ll be on the next flight to Ibiza, are you coming with us ?

Created by the team who brought us Experimental Cocktail Clubs in London, Paris and New York, the drinks at the Experimental Beach in Ibiza may be of the same exceptional quality, but the feel is very different.

The beach club decor looks to 60s Ibiza, channeling a hippy, bohemian vibe with nautical shades, natural wood and coloured glassware that catches the sunlight bouncing off the sea.

The club’s founders are renowned for their experimental approach and love for rare and unusual spirits; here the margarita is given a hit of local liqueur hierbas and the Pimm’s Punch comes with pomegranate and pineapple – served in sharing punch bowls formed from conch shells and pineapples. 
.

You’ve probably noticed that the low-alcohol trend is on the rise.. so here are 3 easy to make recipes to keep yourself and your guests buzzed and hydrated at your next barbecue.

𝐇𝐮𝐠𝐨
Originating in South Tyrol, but widespread in Triveneto, Austria, Switzerland and Germany, the Hugo is a refreshing, lightly alcoholic aperitif made with prosecco, elderflower syrup, seltzer and mint leaves.

𝐒𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐭-𝐅𝐥𝐨𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐭
An easy-drinking aperitif that can be made slightly more potent by adding gin. But we love it without, too.

𝐒𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐤𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐆𝐢𝐧 𝐁𝐚𝐬𝐢𝐥 𝐋𝐞𝐦𝐨𝐧𝐚𝐝𝐞
A deliciously herbal concoction made more impactful by muddling your herbs. The basil can be replaced with tarragon if you have some handy.
.

Some of your favorite bars have been dabbling in crafting their own spirits, to stellar results.

Our friends at Singapore bar Atlas partnered up with Californian distillery St George’s Spirits for the creation of this truly special, citrus-forward gin

New York City’s The Dead Rabbit’s Belfast-born founders collaborated with The Dublin Liberties Distillery’s master distiller to launch this five-year-old blend of Irish single malt and grain whiskeys, first aged for five years in seasoned Bourbon casks, and finished in small virgin American oak barrels.

The Connaught Bar Gin uses a classic London gin recipe as its base, with botanicals including juniper berries, coriander seeds, liquorice, angelica root and orris root.

The Savoy’s Beaufort Bar partnered with Northern Ireland’s Boatyard Distillery on this 43% ABV vodka made from wheat, Champagne yeast and water

The Gibson released their savory-led gin last year in partnership with Belgium’s Copperhead Distillery, made with 5 Copperhead botanicals and 13 spices traditionally used in pickling such as pepper, allspice and fennel.
.
.
.

Want to discover a Parisian gem ? It’s Candelaria : A true hidden gem, Candelaria, a popular bar, offers some of the best Mexican top cocktails and food in Paris.

This semi-hidden space is dinky and full of character, with its rough-hewn walls and candle-lit, cushion-strewn interior if you go when it’s a bit quieter it’s a great place to take a date, and it’s proved itself a hit with the younger, hipper crowd. Be sure to sample the superior tacos and quesadillas before kicking off your tequila-fest or maybe the frijoles or veggie tostadas?

The margaritas are also worth a look and there’s a Mexican beer on offer as well, or order some of the tasty punch. The bar staff are friendly, so if you don’t see anything you like they will usually make up cocktails to suit your tastes if you ask nicely.
.

The difference between a perfectly balanced Mojito or Manhattan and a flavorless, watered-down drink goes right down to your choice of ice cubes.

Choosing the right kind of ice isn’t as easy as it seems! 

𝐈𝐜𝐞 𝐜𝐮𝐛𝐞𝐬
The foundation to a refreshing drink, trusty ice cubes are the most commonly used type of ice in homemade cocktails.
In an “on the rocks” cocktail, it is therefore best to use extra-large ice cubes (around 5 cm per side), to provide a longer-lasting chill with minimum dilution.

𝐂𝐫𝐮𝐬𝐡𝐞𝐝 𝐢𝐜𝐞
Crushed ice melts quicker than ice cubes, blending harmoniously with your chilled and slushy cocktails. The Zombie is a famous example of a crushed ice spectacular, as is the Mojito.

𝐀𝐥𝐥 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐰𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐜𝐞
For a more cultivated alternative, whiskey stones allow you to chill your drink without affecting its taste 
.
.
.

Oriole is a sleek and contemporary cocktail den proffering a fusion of Old and New Worlds and the exotic Orient.
In true speakeasy bar style, you’ll find Oriole tucked away in underground Farringdon in London, with a low-key, unassuming entrance within the deserted Smithfield Market.
Now delve into the huge cocktail bible – this could take a while! It’s rather overwhelming, organised by Old World, New World and The Orient. Featuring all sorts of fantastical ingredients from across the globe, like nopal purée, or Voatsiperifery infusion. 

When it comes to ordering at Oriole, be adventurous, because you really won’t find drinks like this anywhere else.

We met San Francisco-born @jessejvida for our Savoir Faire project, a few months ago. Named head bartender at the iconic Singaporean venue back in November 2018, after over a decade in the industry where the self-taught mixologist worked his way up to some of the best bars in New York City.  Jesse’s growing need for change was met with a perfectly-timed, once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. Singapore was calling, and to work at the breathtaking ATLAS Bar, no less.  Just shy of two years into his tenure, we caught up with Vida to find out how he has settled into this new role, share some of his expert tips with our readers, and find out what’s changed at ATLAS  Bar.  Discover our interview with Jesse Vida.
